The term “improper worship” encompasses both '''exceeding one’s due share in worship''' and '''worship not included in the sacrificial canon'''. Chinese deities are divided into three major categories: [[:en:Tenjin|Heavenly Deities]], {{ill|Earthly Deities|de|Irdische Gottheiten|ja|地祇|zh|地祇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Earthly Deities|qq=}}, and {{ill|Human Ghosts|de|Menschliche Geister|ja|人鬼|zh|人鬼|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Human Ghosts|qq=}}<ref>《{{ill|Zhou Li|de|Zhou-Li|ja|周禮|zh|周禮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zhou Li|qq=}}·Spring Officials·Grand Ancestor》: “Overseeing the rites of the heavenly deities, human ghosts, and earthly deities who establish the nation.”</ref>. Here, irrespective of whether one considers heavenly deities, earthly deities (or {{ill|Spirits of Things|de|Geister der Dinge|ja|物精|zh|物精|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Spirits of Things|qq=}}), the focus is solely on human ghosts. According to the sacrificial regulations recorded in the [[:en:Book of Rites|Book of Rites]]: “In the system of rites established by the sage-kings, those benefitting the people are venerated; those who die in dedicated service are honored; those who labor to secure the state are celebrated; those capable of repelling great calamities are revered; and those able to avert major misfortunes are worshiped.” Thus, apart from the ancestors venerated by every household, only individuals who have rendered meritorious service to the state or local community are entitled to be honored.

Although meritorious individuals are deserving of veneration, worshiping that which is not rightfully one’s due is also considered “improper worship”. For example, in the region of [[:en:江南|Jiangnan]], there formerly existed the “Three High Temples” which honored [[:en:Fan Li|Fan Li]], {{ill|Zhang Han (Jin Dynasty)|de|Zhang Han (Jin-Dynastie)|ja|張翰 (晉朝)|lt=Zhang Han|lt_ja=張翰|lt_de=Zhang Han|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zhang Han (Jin Dynasty)|qq=}}, and {{ill|Lu Guimeng|de|Lu Guimeng|ja|陸龜蒙|zh|陸龜蒙|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Lu Guimeng|qq=}}, as well as the “Three Loyal Temples” which venerated {{ill|Wu Yuan|de|Wu Yuan|ja|伍員|zh|伍員|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wu Yuan|qq=}}, [[:en:Zhang Xun (Tang dynasty)|Zhang Xun]], and [[:en:Yue Fei|Yue Fei]]. However, scholars generally held that the “Three High Temples” should not venerate Fan Li, because he once offered beauties and precious objects to seduce the King of Wu—thus becoming an enemy of the people of Wu: “If the rites do not honor one’s own clan, how could one possibly venerate an enemy?” Therefore, he should not be honored. Although Zhang Xun and Yue Fei were loyal, having no ties with the Wu region they should not be venerated; to do so would constitute improper worship: “In ancient times, those who rendered meritorious service to the people were enshrined in temples for a hundred generations. Was it that they had no rightful place, and yet they were exploited by foolish men and women?”<ref>《{{ill|Gazetteer of Wujiang County: Temples and Shrines|de|Wujiang-County Gazetteer: Temples and Shrines|ja|吳江縣志·祠廟|zh|吳江縣志·祠廟|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gazetteer of Wujiang County: Temples and Shrines|qq=}}》 states: “Now, in the records of temples and shrines, if one is forced to be strict and slightly relaxes the guidelines, then the unworthy will eventually exploit this precedent—selling their treachery, and when the people follow suit in their investigations, the trend will become unstoppable. In ancient times, those who rendered meritorious service to the people were enshrined in temples for a hundred generations. Was it that they had no rightful place, and yet they were exploited by foolish men and women?”</ref>

== Improper Worship in History ==
Improper worship—that which stands in opposition to the deities recognized by the state as orthodox—has consistently been ridiculed by scholars and, at times, forcibly suppressed. For example, during the reign of {{ill|Emperor Ping|de|Kaiser Ping|ja|平帝|zh|平帝|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Ping|qq=}} of the {{ill|Western Han|de|Westliche Han-Dynastie|ja|西漢|zh|西漢|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Western Han|qq=}}, there was the decree “Ban the dissemination of teachings, prohibit improper worship, and permit the sounds of Zheng.” During the {{ill|Eastern Han|de|Östliche Han-Dynastie|ja|東漢|zh|東漢|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Eastern Han|qq=}}, {{ill|Diwulun|de|Diwulun|ja|第五倫|zh|第五倫|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Diwulun|qq=}} decreed “Ban and eradicate improper worship, and the people will be at peace.” At the end of the Eastern Han, [[:en:Cao Cao|Cao Cao]] ordered “Ban and sever improper worship; illicit relations and the flight of offenders led to a solemnity along county boundaries.” Later, {{ill|Emperor Wen of Wei|de|Kaiser Wen von Wei|ja|魏文帝|zh|魏文帝|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Wen of Wei|qq=}} issued an edict stating, “From now on, whoever dares to establish a rite not conforming to propriety, or whose shamanic words are uttered, shall be dealt with as following the heterodox path, as inscribed in the law.” Similarly, {{ill|Emperor Ming of Wei|de|Kaiser Ming von Wei|ja|魏明帝|zh|魏明帝|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Ming of Wei|qq=}} decreed, “For those mountains and rivers in the counties not included in the sacrificial canon, do not venerate them.” During the reign of {{ill|Emperor Wu of Jin|de|Kaiser Wu von Jin|ja|晉武帝|zh|晉武帝|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Wu of Jin|qq=}}, an edict stated “If it is not in the sacrificial canon, remove it.” Emperor Ming of the [[:en:Northern Wei|Northern Wei]] decreed “Ban improper worship, and burn all miscellaneous deities.” In the [[:en:Northern Zhou|Northern Zhou]], [[:en:Emperor Wu|Emperor Wu]] ordered “Ban all improper worship; expel anything not recorded in the liturgical canon.” In the period of the {{ill|Southern and Northern Dynasties|de|Süd- und Nord-Dynastien|ja|南北朝|lt=Southern Dynasty|lt_ja=南朝|lt_de=Süd-Dynastie|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Southern and Northern Dynasties|qq=}}, during the reign of {{ill|Emperor Wu of Song|de|Kaiser Wu von Song|ja|宋武帝|zh|宋武帝|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Wu of Song|qq=}}, it was decreed “Ban improper worship; eliminate all local temples.”

Because the definition of “improper worship” was formulated by official standards, the deities thus venerated were deemed proper, yet at the same time were regarded as lewd, demonic, and perverse spirits. Prior to the Six Dynasties, [[:en:Buddhism|Buddhism]] in China was largely considered by scholars to be “a foreign deity not worthy of v

